    {
        "user": "UJBAJNFLK",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1776188058.923979",
        "client_msg_id": "0fd41c62-0abd-4a11-9df1-ed7e988b7992",
        "text": "Running coding agents backwards is a possibility. But not a trivial problem to solve. The \"factbase\" is what, exactly? For the code I deal with, it would have to include mathematical relations between numbers. The code being an approximation (floats etc) to the relations that one would like to see recovered. Not impossible, given that the number of numerical algorithms is limited and an LLM could have seen them all. But the structure of the factbase is part of the design that needs to be recovered. I don't know if an LLM can deal with that.\n\nAnd then there is the eternal question with LLMs: do you trust the output to be correct, or at least good enough? Much of the legacy code we are using has no tests, no specification, etc. It's just the code, plus input\/output combinations (which are easy to produce).",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "e169f54bbaf8",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2021-03-12\/1859691333940_e169f54bbaf8b9b36b12_72.png",
            "first_name": "Konrad",
            "real_name": "Konrad Hinsen",
            "display_name": "Konrad Hinsen",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "konrad.hinsen",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1776169365.415839",
        "parent_user_id": "UGWUJUZHT",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "5ec+K",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Running coding agents backwards is a possibility. But not a trivial problem to solve. The \"factbase\" is what, exactly? For the code I deal with, it would have to include mathematical relations between numbers. The code being an approximation (floats etc) to the relations that one would like to see recovered. Not impossible, given that the number of numerical algorithms is limited and an LLM could have seen them all. But the structure of the factbase is part of the design that needs to be recovered. I don't know if an LLM can deal with that.\n\nAnd then there is the eternal question with LLMs: do you trust the output to be correct, or at least good enough? Much of the legacy code we are using has no tests, no specification, etc. It's just the code, plus input\/output combinations (which are easy to produce)."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
